SOMEONE WROTE THAT SHE STARTED TO LEARN URDU TO UNDERSTAND SUFI MUSIC. 
I must say you have taken a very very good step.. I mostly recommend foreigners to learn local languages to understand the real msg inside sufi poetry. Aap ne bohat acha kam kiya Urdu seekh kar. Actually, now are able to talk with 1 billion and 50 crore people of Subcontinent(Pakistan, India and Bangladesh). They are all Urdu (Pakistan) and Hindi(India and Bangladesh) speakers. Urdu and Hindi are same in speaking that's why I am from Pakistan and Pakistani people watch Indian Dramas and Movies and India watch Pakistani Dramas easily. They have just 2 little differences, 1) Urdu use Arabic script and Hindi Use Sanskrit(Hindu religious language) .. (2) Hindi and Urdu are nearly 1% different in vocabulary.  That;s it. :) Love and Peace from Pakistan and Wish you very very good luck. Talk with more and more Hindi and Urdu speakers. It will help you very much ..

Actually, there is a lot of difference in Sufiana or Sufi Music and New Music Produced in whole world and more specifically Subcontinent(Pakistan, India, Bangladesh). Modern Music have just love of girls etc.. you know fast and whatever. They loose their fame after some time but Sufi Music is totally opposite. Today as compared to past, more people attract towards Sufism and Sufi Poetry. As told by Allah in Quran about thinking and diving in God's sea of Love, Sufi Poetry gives us invitation to think about it's each and every word and explore the world inside it. But Today, you know no one have time to think what the poet's msg really is.  
Sufi Music emphasize on Love of Allah. Sufi Poets expressed their feeling through poetry and their poetry is a beacon of light in darkness If we want to reach Allah.. Thanks very much.

snippet.textDisplay: Guitar and piano blend well with any genre of music, but western drums and many electronic percussion instruments don't. Music organizers and composers are often seen trying to mix these 'incompatible' sounds with distinctive musical styles such as Sufi and Ghazal music all in a bid to appeal to the audience who cannot not appreciate classical nuances and generally only enjoy louder and faster drum beats. But such attempts not only result in upsetting the musical equilibrium of the distinctive genres but they also strip them of their musical elegance. Coke Studio musical performances are a good example of that.
